Q) I have XXXX for trade, are you interested?
A) NO, thank you, but not interested in any trades.

A) NO, through the FFL, sorry

A) Again, that isn't a question, that is a statement. If you can get it here or there for this or that, GREAT, go get it. I know what the prices are locally and online and mine is well within reason, even for a used Glock.

title: For Sale:  LineSiders: We Consign Guns
location: Land O Lakes, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
LineSiders Outfitters is a hunting, fishing, camping and firearms consignment store. We are currently accepting firearms on consignment. We are open Monday - Saturday 10am-6pm. 

Benefits Of Gun Consignment
We've been asked several times about gun consignment both how it works and why we keep a percentage of the final sale price.

First, when you consign a gun with us we take the hassle and burden out of selling a firearm to an unknown individual. Federal law requires us to file the appropriate paperwork that takes the gun out of your name and into the name of the buyer. We cover the expense of background checks, paperwork and insurance. 

Second, we not only market guns locally but we also list many of them nationally. With an FFL, we are able to ship the guns to other FFL's without too much hassle. Forget answering a ton of questions from online inquiries, taking a bunch of photos and then communicating with the purchasing party to coordinate shipping to their FFL. 

Third, we understand some people have no clue when it comes to guns. Either it was passed down from generation to generation or even received as a birthday gift, Christmas present or Fathers Day surprise. We are always willing to help someone come up with a value for a gun. The choice is yours to consign it with us or sell it using one of the online auctions or local newspapers. We can even help you with the private transaction for a nominal fee.

Had this posted earlier in the year and a couple trade deals did not work out. Let it sit for a while now it is time to re-list it.

Bought about 3 years ago, because I just had to try a Glock. Well, I’ve tried but they just don’t fit my hands well and I hate just letting it sit in the safe. It is a great shooting pistol, has been completely reliable and accurate. I bought it used, so I do not know the actual round count, but I don’t believe it to be very many (look at the wear on the outside of barrel – not much there). I have personally only put (60) – (75) .40 rounds through it and (32) 9mm rounds. Since I have owned it, I have added the following;

-(3) Additional standard capacity magazines – LE Marked, if that matters to you.
-Trijicon “Operator” night sights. They are 2008 vintage and still have plenty of glow to them.
-Crimson Trace Grip mounted laser – Not currently installed. Works very well. Have original box and tools.
-KKM .40 to 9mm conversion barrel, bought used, previous owner claimed about one hundred rounds through it. I have put another (32) through it. It is actually for a long slide model (35?), but fits and functions just fine. I had plans to get it threaded, but never ended up doing it. 
-(2) standard capacity 9mm mags and (1) 10-round 9mm mag.

As for condition, everything looks really good except for some very light finish wear near the muzzle end of the slide and on the slide release. As far as value goes, here is what I am figuring (I could be wrong too);
-Pistol, box, (1) magazine and orig. accessories = $400 
-(3) additional magazines @ $20.00 each = $ 60.00
-Trijicon Operator Night Sights = $100.00
-Crimson Trace grip mounted laser = $125.00
-KKM .40 to 9mm conversion barrel = $100.00
-(2) Standard capacity 9mm mags at $20.00 ea. = $40.00
-(1) 10-round capacity 9mm mag at $15.00 = $15.00

Subtotal = $840 

I am asking $725 (dropped from $800)  (Prefer to sell or trade this as a package.)

Depending on your trade, the trade could be + cash on either side. Also have some Speer Lawman ammunition I might be convinced to part with as part of a trade.

Trade interests, in no particular order; CZ P-01, CZ SP-01, CZ P-09, CZ Rifles (prefer .223, .308), VZ 58, Dan Wesson 1911, Colt 1911, Springfield Loaded, Marlin 1894 in .357 (might consider a .44 as well) – needs to be JM marked, Aimpoint - Comp M4 or Micro, Smith & Wesson MP 15-22, Smith & Wesson Shield in 9mm - combinations of these and knives or silver or maybe something else I haven’t thought of – the worst I could say is a polite “no thank you”.

It is in the original 7.65x53 Argentine, unlike it`s thousands of similar sporters, which were converted to .30-06. In my limited experience, I`ve found that it is a lot cheaper than .30-06 too.
